SENATE . . . . . . . . . . . . . . No. 1461
By Mr. Moore, a petition (accompanied by resolve, Senate, No. 1461) of Michael O. Moore that
provisions be made for an investigation and study by a special commission (including members
of the General Court) relative to the use and effectiveness of the zoning approval process of
educational uses under the so-called Dover amendment. Municipalities and Regional
Government.
[SIMILAR MATTER FILED IN PREVIOUS SESSION
SEE SENATE, NO. 1312 OF 2023-2024.]
The Commonwealth of Massachusetts
_______________
In the One Hundred and Ninety-Fourth General Court
(2025-2026)
_______________
Resolve establishing a special commission on the Dover amendment.
1 Resolved, there shall be a special commission to study the use and effectiveness of the
2 zoning approval process of educational uses under the so-called Dover amendment, section 3 of
3 chapter 40A of the General Laws.
4 The commission shall consist of the secretary of housing and economic development or a
5 designee, who shall serve as chair; the secretary of the executive office of education or a
6 designee; 2 members appointed by the president of the senate, including the senate chair of the
7 joint committee on municipalities and regional government and the senate chair of the joint
8 committee housing; 1 member appointed by the senate minority leader; 2 members appointed by
9 the speaker of the house of representatives, including the house chair of the joint committee on
10 municipalities and regional government and the house chair of the joint committee housing; 1
1 of 2

11 member appointed by the house minority leader and 3 members to be appointed by the governor,
12 1 of whom shall be a local official with expertise in zoning, 1 of whom shall be a member of a
13 non-profit social services agency and 1 of whom shall be a member of a non-profit school or
14 higher education institution.
15 The commission shall study the impact of the education exemption provided by the
16 Dover amendment on municipalities and nonprofit education institutions, which shall include a
17 review of the types of building projects sited under the protection of the Dover amendment and
18 the case law decided on the educational exemption. The commission shall solicit public
19 testimony, either by holding public hearings or through surveys.
20 The commission shall file the results of its study together with recommendations for
21 legislation, which shall include a proposed definition of “educational purposes”, with the clerks
22 of the house of representatives and senate, on or before January 1, 2026.
